#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:295
msgid "Rebuilding & cleaning the workspace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:297
msgid ""
"Rebuilding NumPy after making changes to compiled code can be done with the "
"same build command as you used previously - only the changed files will be "
"re-built.  Doing a full build, which sometimes is necessary, requires "
"cleaning the workspace first.  The standard way of doing this is (*note: "
"deletes any uncommitted files!*)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:303
msgid "$ git clean -xdf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:305
msgid ""
"When you want to discard all changes and go back to the last commit in the "
"repo, use one of::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:308
msgid ""
"$ git checkout .\n"
"$ git reset --hard"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:315
msgid "Debugging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:317
msgid ""
"Another frequently asked question is \"How do I debug C code inside NumPy?"
"\". First, ensure that you have gdb installed on your system with the Python "
"extensions (often the default on Linux). You can see which version of Python "
"is running inside gdb to verify your setup::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:322
msgid ""
"(gdb) python\n"
">import sys\n"
">print(sys.version_info)\n"
">end\n"
"sys.version_info(major=3, minor=7, micro=0, releaselevel='final', serial=0)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:328
msgid ""
"Most python builds do not include debug symbols and are built with compiler "
"optimizations enabled. To get the best debugging experience using a debug "
"build of Python is encouraged, see :ref:`advanced_debugging`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:332
msgid ""
"In terms of debugging, NumPy also needs to be built in a debug mode. You "
"need to use ``debug`` build type and disable optimizations to make sure ``-"
"O0`` flag is used during object building. Note that NumPy should NOT be "
"installed in your environment before you build with the ``spin build`` "
"command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:337
msgid ""
"To generate source-level debug information within the build process run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:339
msgid "$ spin build --clean -- -Dbuildtype=debug -Ddisable-optimization=true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:343
msgid ""
"In case you are using conda environment be aware that conda sets ``CFLAGS`` "
"and ``CXXFLAGS`` automatically, and they will include the ``-O2`` flag by "
"default. You can safely use ``unset CFLAGS && unset CXXFLAGS`` to avoid them "
"or provide them at the beginning of the ``spin`` command: ``CFLAGS=\"-O0 -"
"g\" CXXFLAGS=\"-O0 -g\"``. Alternatively, to take control of these variables "
"more permanently, you can create ``env_vars.sh`` file in the ``<path-to-"
"conda-envs>/numpy-dev/etc/conda/activate.d`` directory. In this file you can "
"export ``CFLAGS`` and ``CXXFLAGS`` variables. For complete instructions "
"please refer to https://conda.io/projects/conda/en/latest/user-guide/tasks/"
"manage-environments.html#saving-environment-variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:354
msgid ""
"Next you need to write a Python script that invokes the C code whose "
"execution you want to debug. For instance ``mytest.py``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:357
msgid ""
"import numpy as np\n"
"x = np.arange(5)\n"
"np.empty_like(x)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:361
msgid ""
"Note that your test file needs to be outside the NumPy clone you have. Now, "
"you can run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:364
msgid "$ spin gdb /path/to/mytest.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:366
msgid "In case you are using clang toolchain::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:368
msgid "$ spin lldb /path/to/mytest.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:370
msgid "And then in the debugger::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:372
msgid ""
"(gdb) break array_empty_like\n"
"(gdb) run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:375
msgid "lldb counterpart::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:377
msgid ""
"(lldb) breakpoint set --name array_empty_like\n"
"(lldb) run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:380
msgid ""
"The execution will now stop at the corresponding C function and you can step "
"through it as usual. A number of useful Python-specific commands are "
"available. For example to see where in the Python code you are, use ``py-"
"list``, to see the python traceback, use ``py-bt``.  For more details, see "
"`DebuggingWithGdb`_. Here are some commonly used commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:386
msgid "``list``: List specified function or line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:387
msgid "``next``: Step program, proceeding through subroutine calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:388
msgid "``step``: Continue program being debugged, after signal or breakpoint."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:389
msgid "``print``: Print value of expression EXP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:391
msgid ""
"Rich support for Python debugging requires that the ``python-gdb.py`` script "
"distributed with Python is installed in a path where gdb can find it. If you "
"installed your Python build from your system package manager, you likely do "
"not need to manually do anything. However, if you built Python from source, "
"you will likely need to create a ``.gdbinit`` file in your home directory "
"pointing gdb at the location of your Python installation. For example, a "
"version of python installed via `pyenv <https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv>`_ "
"needs a ``.gdbinit`` file with the following contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:400
msgid "add-auto-load-safe-path ~/.pyenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:404
msgid ""
"Building NumPy with a Python built with debug support (on Linux "
"distributions typically packaged as ``python-dbg``) is highly recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:416
msgid "Understanding the code & getting started"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:418
msgid ""
"The best strategy to better understand the code base is to pick something "
"you want to change and start reading the code to figure out how it works. "
"When in doubt, you can ask questions on the mailing list. It is perfectly "
"okay if your pull requests aren't perfect, the community is always happy to "
"help. As a volunteer project, things do sometimes get dropped and it's "
"totally fine to ping us if something has sat without a response for about "
"two to four weeks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_environment.rst:425
msgid ""
"So go ahead and pick something that annoys or confuses you about NumPy, "
"experiment with the code, hang around for discussions or go through the "
"reference documents to try to fix it. Things will fall in place and soon "
"you'll have a pretty good understanding of the project as a whole. Good Luck!"
msgstr ""
